  footnotes: []
english:
  title: Farewell to Official Cho-jung of the Bureau of Rites, Upon Receiving the Character 'Fu'
  author: Kim Gwang-jae
  language: eng
  text: |-
    Who serves as wing and feather to raise the royal house?
    Only you stand alone, sovereign of the Three Lands.
    You carry the pure breeze of Fang and Du,
    And like Fu Shuo's rain, you open the sovereign's heart
    With loyal words—becoming both teacher and friend.
    Now, bearing the royal decree, you journey to the court,
    Your great name shall echo through a thousand ages, imperishable.
    As we part, how can mere words console this aching heart?
    Only three verses of Yang Pass and a single cup of wine.
    I pray you, swift be your return from this mission—
    Do not disappoint your mother's love, nor betray the sovereign's grace.
  footnotes:
    - The 'Character Fu' (負字) likely refers to an official title or honor bestowed upon Cho-jung, possibly related to his appointment or promotion.
    - Fang and Du were celebrated advisors to Tang Taizong, representing the ideal of virtuous counsel in Chinese tradition.
    - Fu Shuo was a legendary minister of Shang dynasty, known for his wisdom; his 'rain' symbolizes the nourishment of sage advice.
    - '''Three verses of Yang Pass'' alludes to the famous farewell song, evoking the bittersweet tradition of parting between friends.'
